Two semiquantitative tests are available for the rapid determination of primarily acetoacetate in urine and blood  although they have never been considered totally satisfactory for blood 
The ferric chloride test is performed by adding  to  drops of freshly voided urine to a few drops of a  solution of ferric chloride 
At first  a precipitate of ferric phosphate forms but with additional drops of urine the precipitate disappears and a burgundy red color appears 
The intensity of the color is judged + to + 
The assay measures only acetoacetate and its sensitivity is less than  mgdl 
Unfortunately  drugs such as salicylates and antipyrines  as well as phenols  acetates  and cyanates  will cause false positive results 
To overcome this the sample is boiled for  minutes to remove the unstable acetoacetate  which causes the red color to disappear 
It is preferable to repeat the test on a previously boiled urine sample 
The sodium nitroprusside reaction measures both acetone and acetoacetate  but not hydroxybutyrate  in biological materials 
There is no interference from most drugs and metabolic products 
It is the most successful test devised 
For the Rothera test A named for the originator of the test   gm ammonium sulfate is added to  ml urine and  after shaking to dissolve   drops of freshly prepared sodium nitroprusside solution is added 
After mixing   to  ml of a saturated solution of ammonium hydroxide is layered onto the sample and after  minutes  the purple color which forms at the interface is judged for its intensity from  + to  + 
The nitroprusside test will detect  to  mgdl acetoacetate or  mgdl acetone 
In a less sensitive but perhaps more convenient assay Rothera test B  a solution of ammonium sulfate is used and the reagents are mixed with the specimen so that the entire solution becomes purple 
Ten mgdl acetoacetate or  mgdl acetone can be detected 
To improve the convenience of the assay  the Joslin Clinic formulated a stable  dry preparation of sodium nitroprusside by combining it with ammonium sulfate  gm to  gm  respectively 
Two to  ml of urine are saturated with this mixture  and the purple color at the interface is read  to  minutes after overlaying with ammonium hydroxide 
The color intensity is from a purplish pink to deep purple and is scored  + to  +  but it deteriorates with standing 
The ferric chloride and nitroprusside tests are still in clinical use in developing nations 
